    <bioghist encodinganalog="545">
      <p>Frederick G. Sampson II was born in Port Arthur, Texas on August 9, 1928 and started his career teaching mathematics in his hometown. His work as a Baptist minister began in Texarkana, Arkansas and eventually led him to the Tabernacle Missionary Baptist Church in Detroit, where he served from 1971 until his death in 2001.</p>
      <p>Dr. Sampson earned numerous degrees: two bachelors from Bishop College; bachelor's and a master's degree from Howard University; and master's degrees from Columbus State University and the University of Louisville. He earned his doctoral degree from Virginia Theological Seminary and earned certificates and honorary degrees from several other colleges and universities. In 1984 and again in 1993 <title render="italic">Ebony Magazine</title> named Dr. Sampson one of the 15 Greatest Black Preachers in America.</p>
      <p>Dr. Sampson lectured at colleges and universities across the country, conducted numerous yearly revivals, created study courses and other materials for the Baptists and for the YMCA, and broadcast regularly on the radio. His work included conducting conferences on black male spirituality, planning the 1965 voting rights march with Dr. Martin Luther King Jr., and serving as president of the Detroit branch of the NAACP.</p>
    </bioghist>
    <scopecontent encodinganalog="520">
      <p>The Frederick G. Sampson collection includes personal and church related papers that document his professional work and church activities from 1970 until his death in 2001. In addition, there is some information about the Foundation established in his name. The papers are arranged in the following series: Pastoral Career and Personal Papers.</p>
    </scopecontent>
